~ start
Rocky: [speed=0.5]I can't believe I finally got my own office. Let's head inside to see how it looks.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]You can interact with objects that have a yellow highlight when you hover over them with your mouse.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Move your mouse over the door and click your left mouse button to interact with it.
=> END

~ tutorial1
Rocky: [speed=0.5]The office looks good. I should check and make sure everything is all set for when I get a client.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Let's start by checking out my filing cabinet. It holds all our files on common cyber threats our clients will most likely face.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Try interacting with the filing cabinet to your right. Simply direct your mouse to it and left click when highlighted.
=> END

~ tutorial2
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Try clicking on the one of the file tabs to see descriptions of each cyber threat.
=> END

~ tutorial3
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Good job. You can check out the other tabs if you want. When ready, try going back by hitting the return button in the top center of the screen to return to the office.
=> END

~ tutorial4
Rocky: [speed=0.5]The filing cabinet seems to be in order. Lets check out our clue board hanging on the left wall.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Move your mouse over the clue board and click when highlighted.
=> END

~ tutorial5
Rocky: [speed=0.5]This is where the details of your client's case will be displayed.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]You can click on a clue to get further details about it.
=> END

~ tutorial6
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Good job. This will show the details of each clue that you will investigate.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Now try clicking return to go back to the clueboard overview.
=> END

~ tutorial7
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Good job. Now click return once more to return to the office.
=> END

~ tutorial8
Rocky: [speed=0.5]The clue board is ready to go.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Now lets check our journal by pressing the space bar.
=> END

~ tutorial9
Rocky: [speed=0.5]This is your journal. It will be updated every time you look at a clue on the clue board.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]You will use this journal to try and figure out which clue is the cause of the clients problem.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]You can type your thoughts for the case questions to help you solve the case.
Rocky: [speed=0.5]Now click the close button to return to the office.
=> END

~ tutorial10
Rocky: [speed=0.5] *knock at the door* Sounds like we have our first client...
=> END


~ level1a
Carla: [speed=0.5] Hello deary, I've come to you with an inquiry. I woke up yesterday morning with my bank account empty!
Rocky: [speed=0.5] How awful! Did you do anything specific yesterday?
Carla: [speed=0.5] The only thing of note I did was go through my emails for the day.
Rocky: [speed=0.5] Do you mind if I take a look at your emails from yesterday?
Carla: [speed=0.5] Not at all!
=> END

~ level1b
Rocky: [speed=0.5] Am I confident I know the type of cyber threat and the clue that caused it?
Rocky: [speed=0.5] You can use the arrow keys and enter to select a choice.
 - Yes
	Rocky: [speed=0.5] Carla I think I know what happened.
	Rocky: [speed=0.5] The cyber threat that allowed someone to steal your money was a...
	 - Phishing
		Rocky: [speed=0.5] A PHISHING ATTACK!! And the email behind the attack was...
		 - Email 1: Rajah
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] FROM RAJAH. If thats even his real name. I recognize this kind of pattern anywhere.
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] This is Phineas's doing! Listen Carla, you never give out your bank information to someone online!
			Carla: [speed=0.5] But I thought it was going to a good cause, what should I look out for?
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] Look at the email address, it's made up of random letters and numbers. You shouldn't trust an emailer unless you know who really they are.
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] Strangers online, especially ones from email addresses you don't know, should never ask you for money or bank information. 
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] Especially if they make the situation sound urgent. Thats a common tactic to getting you to click their links.
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] Random links attached to the email should never be clicked. Especially if its doesn't start with https, which is more secure than links that start with http.
			Carla: [speed=0.5] Wow, thanks Rocky! I've learned so much.
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] Of course, I've contacted the authorities who can hopefully help you recover your money.
			=> END
		 - Email 2: Alice 
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] FROM ALICE!! No wait! This can't be right. I should reinvestigate my clues.
			=> END
		 - Email 3: Tony 
			Rocky: [speed=0.5] FROM TONY!! No wait! This can't be right. I should reinvestigate my clues.
			=> END
	 - Spyware
		Rocky: [speed=0.5] THROUGH SPYWARE!! No wait! this can't be it. I should revisit my filing cabinet.
		=> END
	 - Social Media Impersonation
		Rocky: [speed=0.5] THROUGH SOCIAL MEDIA IMPERSONATION!! No wait! this can't be it. I should revisit my filing cabinet.
		=> END
